00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:48.490
2 plus 2 equals window.

00:48:48.490 --> 00:48:49.850
RICH MOORE: Yeah.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:51.520
AUDIENCE: So my question to
you is, how do you as a

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:54.380
director keep your
team motivated,

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:55.760
especially your artists?

00:48:55.760 --> 00:48:59.220
Since it's such a
long endeavor.

00:48:59.220 --> 00:49:00.440
RICH MOORE: That's
a good question.

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:02.280
Well, it is a long endeavor.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:07.010
And we worked for four
years on this movie.

00:49:07.010 --> 00:49:11.880
And sometimes animated films
can go on for eight years.

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:14.120
There's some that have gone on
for 10 years in development

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:16.780
and production.

00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:23.170
And what's interesting is,
too, it's a very non

00:49:23.170 --> 00:49:25.640
spontaneous process.

00:49:25.640 --> 00:49:31.380
And my job is to, by the end,
make the whole experience,

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:33.790
what the audience is seeing,
feel as if they're watching it

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:39.590
kind of happen right before
their eyes as if it was live

00:49:39.590 --> 00:49:42.490
action captured on film.

00:49:42.490 --> 00:49:50.040
So I would say the way that I
kind of keep that exciting or

00:49:50.040 --> 00:49:57.160
spontaneous is just we challenge
each other in making

00:49:57.160 --> 00:50:01.650
the artwork or the performance
the best it can be.

00:50:01.650 --> 00:50:05.580
I think that I work with a group
of people that really

00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:08.760
want the best out of everything
that they do.

00:50:08.760 --> 00:50:13.930
So they're looking to
me for guidance on

00:50:13.930 --> 00:50:15.180
this kind of thing.

00:50:21.220 --> 00:50:31.250
What keeps it interesting and
satisfying for the artists and

00:50:31.250 --> 00:50:36.010
myself is that I remind
myself I'm a director.

00:50:36.010 --> 00:50:37.260
I'm not a dictator.

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:41.790
I'm not there to dictate to
someone, no, do it like this.

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:42.770
I want it yellow.

00:50:42.770 --> 00:50:46.060
And I want it like this,
and I want-- you know.

00:50:46.060 --> 00:50:51.960
My job is to kind of bring out
what this person can bring to

00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:54.010
the idea, not tell them.

00:50:54.010 --> 00:50:56.600
To me, they're not
just a wrist.

00:50:56.600 --> 00:51:01.050
And that's where the best of
someone comes-- the best of an

00:51:01.050 --> 00:51:05.070
artist or technician or
production person

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:08.420
working on the movie.

00:51:08.420 --> 00:51:15.550
So I always try to encourage the
crew to take ownership of

00:51:15.550 --> 00:51:18.210
what they're doing,
to not look to me

00:51:18.210 --> 00:51:20.180
for the final answer.

00:51:20.180 --> 00:51:22.770
Like, I'm not going to tell
you exactly how to do it.

00:51:22.770 --> 00:51:26.810
I want you to discover it,
because you are going to bring

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:29.650
something to it that I'm
not thinking of.

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:33.400
Your point of view is going
to make it better.

00:51:33.400 --> 00:51:35.600
So I try not to dictate.

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:39.350
I try not to tell people exactly
how they should do it,

00:51:39.350 --> 00:51:42.380
because to me, there's
no fun in that.

00:51:42.380 --> 00:51:46.210
It's not fun for me, it's
not fun for the artist.

00:51:46.210 --> 00:51:49.770
The fun is to kind of watch the
thing grow as different

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:53.740
minds are kind of put onto it.

00:51:53.740 --> 00:51:54.390
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:54.390 --> 00:51:56.730
So I was delighted by the way
you captured the essence of

00:51:56.730 --> 00:52:01.340
the '80s era video games like
Donkey Kong and Rampage and

00:52:01.340 --> 00:52:03.730
Elevator Action in the
Wreck-It Ralph game.

00:52:03.730 --> 00:52:04.380
RICH MOORE: Thank you.

00:52:04.380 --> 00:52:08.390
AUDIENCE: I'm curious, what was
your creative process for

00:52:08.390 --> 00:52:09.450
imagining that game?

00:52:09.450 --> 00:52:12.330
And what was the technical
process for

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:13.360
developing the visuals?

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.500
RICH MOORE: The actual game?

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:16.090
What we did is--

00:52:16.090 --> 00:52:18.200
and that was one of the first
things that we kind of dove

00:52:18.200 --> 00:52:23.910
into was the actual gameplay, or
just concept of that world,

00:52:23.910 --> 00:52:25.200
what it was about.

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:31.350
And the process was working with
the story crew and the

00:52:31.350 --> 00:52:35.240
design crew of just kind
of creating boards.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:38.260
First, putting up images of
games that we thought that

00:52:38.260 --> 00:52:39.580
this was like.

00:52:39.580 --> 00:52:40.940
It's kind of like Donkey Kong.

00:52:40.940 --> 00:52:43.690
It's kind of like Rampage.

00:52:43.690 --> 00:52:50.540
And then breaking down, like,
what made those games unique?

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:52.800
How much detail did
they have to them?

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:54.960
What were the goals?

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:59.440
And what made them appealing?

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:05.100
And then beginning a lot of
visual just boards of

00:53:05.100 --> 00:53:08.040
different people's ideas of what
can the gameplay be like,

00:53:08.040 --> 00:53:13.400
starting with this idea of one
guy fixes, one guy wrecks.

00:53:13.400 --> 00:53:16.280
And it was months and
months and months.

00:53:16.280 --> 00:53:18.780
It did not happen overnight.

00:53:18.780 --> 00:53:22.680
It was a lot of experimentation,
and a lot of

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.770
going back to those old games.

00:53:24.770 --> 00:53:28.400
Because I found, for me, it
was one thing to kind of

00:53:28.400 --> 00:53:33.200
remember them fondly and have
nostalgic feelings for them.

00:53:33.200 --> 00:53:36.160
But to go back and then just
see them again with a more

00:53:36.160 --> 00:53:41.800
critical eye and more kind
of study them was a whole

00:53:41.800 --> 00:53:44.860
different kind of experience
altogether for myself.

00:53:44.860 --> 00:53:49.070
So it was a lot of
trial and error.

00:53:49.070 --> 00:53:51.540
It was a lot of trying different
things and trying to

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:56.340
kind of capture the kind of
off-beat nature of them.

00:53:56.340 --> 00:53:59.600
They're kind of funky
in their concepts.

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:02.770
And that's where the idea of
fixing a broken window with a

00:54:02.770 --> 00:54:06.420
hammer came from, because it
just doesn't make any sense.

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:08.820
But it seemed like, well, but
that seems like what they

00:54:08.820 --> 00:54:11.480
would have had in one
of those old games.

00:54:11.480 --> 00:54:18.520
So we never let logic ruin
of the good ideas.

00:54:18.520 --> 00:54:20.470
And again, it was a lot
of trial and error.

00:54:20.470 --> 00:54:22.620
It was a lot of going
back and forth.

00:54:22.620 --> 00:54:30.280
And then we tried designing kind
of a very crude version

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:32.900
of the game, what the graphics
would look like.

00:54:32.900 --> 00:54:36.000
And I think we did
that in Flash.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:40.880
And as we got further into
production, we knew we wanted

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:43.700
to build an actual cabinet
with the game

00:54:43.700 --> 00:54:45.920
in it that was playable.

00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:52.380
And for that, we went to someone
who programmed games

00:54:52.380 --> 00:54:53.720
back in that time period.

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:56.010
And he used the 8-bit boards.

00:54:56.010 --> 00:54:59.040
And there's a CRT in it.

00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:04.610
We wanted it to be as authentic
as it could be.

00:55:04.610 --> 00:55:10.400
And because of making that one
game, the studio realized,

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:11.430
well, this would be great.

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:14.940
People would love this if we
built a bunch of these things

00:55:14.940 --> 00:55:19.300
and took them around the
country, put them in theaters,

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:23.650
and at old arcades
that still exist.

00:55:23.650 --> 00:55:29.740
So the first one that we built
was made out of a gutted--

00:55:29.740 --> 00:55:31.970
it was a Donkey Kong game.

00:55:31.970 --> 00:55:34.740
So the studio was saying,
we would love 50

00:55:34.740 --> 00:55:36.630
to 60 of these things.

00:55:36.630 --> 00:55:42.680
So not wanting to be the studio
that put 50 Donkey Kong

00:55:42.680 --> 00:55:45.120
cabinets out of commission, we
decided, well, we're going to

00:55:45.120 --> 00:55:47.500
build them from the ground up.

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:50.410
So I think a couple were here.

00:55:50.410 --> 00:55:51.750
Did they bring some over?

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:54.290
RYAN GERMICK: Nobody let
me play anything.

00:55:54.290 --> 00:55:55.490
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:55.490 --> 00:55:57.754
RICH MOORE: Oh, Google,
I am sorry.

00:55:57.754 --> 00:56:00.830
I feel like a jerk now.

00:56:00.830 --> 00:56:01.670
RYAN GERMICK: Thanks a lot.

00:56:01.670 --> 00:56:02.610
Movies in color, everybody.

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:05.194
That's it.

00:56:05.194 --> 00:56:05.686
RICH MOORE: Why?

00:56:05.686 --> 00:56:06.180
Why?

00:56:06.180 --> 00:56:08.420
Why?

00:56:08.420 --> 00:56:11.630
But they did a great job
of weathering them.

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:15.210
They really feel like they're
30 years old, and they play

00:56:15.210 --> 00:56:16.940
very much like those
old games.

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:18.000
I'm really proud of them.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:20.660
And it happened kind of right
in tandem with the movie.

00:56:20.660 --> 00:56:23.390
So we made a movie and a game.

00:56:23.390 --> 00:56:24.420
Ha!

00:56:24.420 --> 00:56:25.200
Pretty good, huh?

00:56:25.200 --> 00:56:26.450
RYAN GERMICK: Not too bad.

00:56:28.510 --> 00:56:29.640
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:56:29.640 --> 00:56:33.290
So in seeing you with your
classmates and hearing you

00:56:33.290 --> 00:56:36.020
talk about them and that
experience, I realized you

00:56:36.020 --> 00:56:39.530
must have been there at the same
time that my roommate's

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:40.680
grandfather was teaching.

00:56:40.680 --> 00:56:42.820
And I was wondering if you could
say something about the

00:56:42.820 --> 00:56:45.080
teachers, and specifically
if you--

00:56:45.080 --> 00:56:46.330
RICH MOORE: Wow, that
makes me feel--

00:56:49.250 --> 00:56:50.520
AUDIENCE: Uh, Bob McCrea.

00:56:50.520 --> 00:56:54.950
RICH MOORE: My father's Daddy
Pop's uncle was there.

00:56:54.950 --> 00:56:57.990
About the teachers that
were at CalArts?

00:56:57.990 --> 00:56:58.700
Who was--

00:56:58.700 --> 00:56:59.520
AUDIENCE: Um, Bob McCrea.

00:56:59.520 --> 00:57:03.300
RICH MOORE: Oh, Bob McCrea was
the director of the program at

00:57:03.300 --> 00:57:07.790
the time, and he was a
wonderful teacher.

00:57:07.790 --> 00:57:10.810
He was someone that worked at
Disney during the golden age

00:57:10.810 --> 00:57:16.360
of animation, and he was kind
of a father figure to us.

00:57:16.360 --> 00:57:21.050
And he had, let's see.

00:57:21.050 --> 00:57:24.550
Hal Ambro was our animation
teacher.

00:57:24.550 --> 00:57:27.480
Our design teacher
was Bob Winquist.

00:57:27.480 --> 00:57:34.100
And Bob Winquest took over for
Bob McCrae, because he became

00:57:34.100 --> 00:57:35.630
ill during our--

00:57:35.630 --> 00:57:37.970
he was very old--

00:57:37.970 --> 00:57:41.830
during our sophomore year, and
Bob became the director of the

00:57:41.830 --> 00:57:45.420
department our junior year.

00:57:45.420 --> 00:57:48.730
And I really, really
loved Bob Winquist.

00:57:51.590 --> 00:57:55.080
Not only was he a great designer
and a great design

00:57:55.080 --> 00:58:01.150
teacher, but he had a way of
talking to us in our class.

00:58:01.150 --> 00:58:03.060
He was very nurturing.

00:58:03.060 --> 00:58:05.750
He really knew how to kind of
bring out the best in people.

00:58:05.750 --> 00:58:10.630
People in our class who did
not consider themselves

00:58:10.630 --> 00:58:15.180
designers, by the end of his
classes really felt like, wow,

00:58:15.180 --> 00:58:17.900
I never knew I could
design something.

00:58:17.900 --> 00:58:19.730
I didn't know I had
this in me.

00:58:19.730 --> 00:58:28.210
So he was just someone that
really fostered feeling in us

00:58:28.210 --> 00:58:33.030
that we could do something
in animation.

00:58:33.030 --> 00:58:37.040
We had one teacher in particular
who felt it was his

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:40.100
job to teach us another
vocation, because he said we

00:58:40.100 --> 00:58:44.580
would never make it in
animation, that animation was

00:58:44.580 --> 00:58:47.480
a dying business, and it
was going nowhere.

00:58:47.480 --> 00:58:49.280
So we really knew
how to paint.

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:53.010
We would have to know how to
paint paintings to be Denny's

00:58:53.010 --> 00:58:55.430
menus covers.

00:58:55.430 --> 00:58:57.690
And he thought he
was helping us.

00:58:57.690 --> 00:59:05.560
But Bob Winquist really
instilled in us this feeling

00:59:05.560 --> 00:59:11.540
that if enough people with a
passion for something were to

00:59:11.540 --> 00:59:14.050
go out in the world, that
you could change it.

00:59:14.050 --> 00:59:19.190
And that you could bring back
an art form that seemed at

00:59:19.190 --> 00:59:20.740
that time to be--

00:59:20.740 --> 00:59:21.800
there's nothing going on.

00:59:21.800 --> 00:59:23.780
It was dead.

00:59:23.780 --> 00:59:32.510
And I credit him a lot for
awakening up our ability to

00:59:32.510 --> 00:59:35.610
have vision for the
future, and our

00:59:35.610 --> 00:59:37.280
careers, and our lives.

00:59:37.280 --> 00:59:38.830
And I miss him a lot.

00:59:38.830 --> 00:59:40.940
He passed away three
years ago.

00:59:40.940 --> 00:59:42.330
And he was a wonderful guy.

00:59:42.330 --> 00:59:47.770
And so many people credit him as
just an instrumental figure

00:59:47.770 --> 00:59:49.040
at that school at the time.

00:59:52.730 --> 00:59:55.260
RYAN GERMICK: Do we have time
for one more question?

00:59:55.260 --> 00:59:56.790
This man came all the way
from Los Angeles.

00:59:56.790 --> 00:59:57.700
RICH MOORE: All the
way from LA.

00:59:57.700 --> 00:59:59.770
RYAN GERMICK: The land of video
game arcades that we'll

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:01.020
never be able to play.

01:00:03.360 --> 01:00:03.960
One more?

01:00:03.960 --> 01:00:05.550
In the middle over here?

01:00:05.550 --> 01:00:06.960
AUDIENCE: So one thing that's
really interesting to me is

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:10.460
you talk a lot about how Ralph
had go back and be redesigned

01:00:10.460 --> 01:00:11.180
several times.

01:00:11.180 --> 01:00:13.210
And the game had to go back
and be redesigned.

01:00:13.210 --> 01:00:16.470
And like, every element it seems
like you chose like 30

01:00:16.470 --> 01:00:19.150
different things before you
finally decided on one.

01:00:19.150 --> 01:00:20.300
Have you ever reached
a point where--

01:00:20.300 --> 01:00:20.600
RICH MOORE: I'm indecisive.

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:21.990
I'm wishy washy.

01:00:21.990 --> 01:00:23.750
RYAN GERMICK: I'm not gonna
tell you what to do.

01:00:23.750 --> 01:00:24.345
It's just gonna--

01:00:24.345 --> 01:00:26.325
RICH MOORE: You know what,
he flip-flops.

01:00:26.325 --> 01:00:27.840
He's a waffler.

01:00:27.840 --> 01:00:30.230
AUDIENCE: So it seems to me like
a movie is a very-- like,

01:00:30.230 --> 01:00:31.500
a really great movie--

01:00:31.500 --> 01:00:33.235
RICH MOORE: I thought we were
gonna have a debate.

01:00:33.235 --> 01:00:35.460
RYAN GERMICK: Yeah,
more conflict.

01:00:35.460 --> 01:00:37.720
AUDIENCE: So my question
basically stems from the fact

01:00:37.720 --> 01:00:40.630
that a great movie seems to be
a very delicate balance of a

01:00:40.630 --> 01:00:41.540
lot of things.

01:00:41.540 --> 01:00:43.860
And in being so indecisive
you find that balance.

01:00:43.860 --> 01:00:46.710
But have you ever gotten maybe
halfway through making a movie

01:00:46.710 --> 01:00:49.530
before realizing your entire
premise was wrong, and either

01:00:49.530 --> 01:00:51.970
giving up or starting
over on everything?

01:00:51.970 --> 01:00:55.750
RICH MOORE: Well, that has not
happened to me, personally.

01:00:55.750 --> 01:00:59.690
But I know some people that
that has happened to.

01:00:59.690 --> 01:01:01.280
So it does exist.

01:01:01.280 --> 01:01:02.600
It does exist.

01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:05.980
Or they won't give up
on the whole thing.

01:01:05.980 --> 01:01:08.590
But they will try to take
elements of something that's

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:12.140
not working and reimagine
it as something else.

01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:19.040
And I think that having
that ability to

01:01:19.040 --> 01:01:20.990
do that at a studio--

01:01:20.990 --> 01:01:22.310
and it sounds scary.

01:01:22.310 --> 01:01:23.940
And it sounds like it's
a horrible thing.

01:01:23.940 --> 01:01:29.450
But some really good movies have
come out of moments like

01:01:29.450 --> 01:01:34.180
that, where they were going in
one direction and turned into

01:01:34.180 --> 01:01:37.310
something else.

01:01:37.310 --> 01:01:42.870
And movies at Pixar, things
like that have happened.

01:01:42.870 --> 01:01:48.050
And I think it speaks a lot to
the management of the studios,

01:01:48.050 --> 01:01:51.770
like Pixar and like Disney, that
are willing to give the

01:01:51.770 --> 01:01:55.950
artist and the directors the
room to make mistakes and to

01:01:55.950 --> 01:02:01.280
try different things and to
really take a stab at

01:02:01.280 --> 01:02:04.240
something and gamble.

01:02:04.240 --> 01:02:06.870
And if it didn't work,
